.\" ************************************************************
.\" _printf(3) - custom formatted output function
.\" Holberton School educational project
.\" ************************************************************
.TH _printf 3 "March 2026" "Holberton" "Library Functions Manual"

.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion (educational implementation)

.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B #include "main.h"
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fB_printf\fR function writes output to standard output according to
\fIformat\fR.

In the current implementation, supported conversion specifiers are:
.IP \(bu 2
\fB%c\fR: print one character
.IP \(bu 2
\fB%s\fR: print one string
.IP \(bu 2
\fB%%\fR: print one percent sign
.IP \(bu 2
\fB%d\fR: print one signed decimal integer
.IP \(bu 2
\fB%i\fR: print one signed decimal integer
.IP \(bu 2
\fB%f\fR: print one floating-point number with 6 digits after the decimal point

For unknown specifiers (example: \fB%q\fR), this implementation prints
both characters literally (\fB%q\fR).

For \fB%s\fR, if the argument is \fBNULL\fR, this implementation prints
\fB(null)\fR.

For \fB%f\fR, this implementation uses a fixed precision of 6 digits
after the decimal point.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, \fB_printf\fR returns the number of characters printed
(excluding the final null byte).

On failure, \fB-1\fR is returned.

Failure cases in this implementation include:
.IP \(bu 2
\fIformat\fR is \fBNULL\fR
.IP \(bu 2
\fIformat\fR ends with a trailing \fB%\fR

.SH ERRORS
This function may fail if an underlying \fBwrite(2)\fR call fails.

.SH LIMITATIONS
This implementation does not yet support:
.IP \(bu 2
unsigned integer conversion (\fB%u\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
octal/hexadecimal conversions (\fB%o\fR, \fB%x\fR, \fB%X\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
pointer conversion (\fB%p\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
flags, field width, precision control and length modifiers

.SH EXAMPLES
.B _printf("Hello %s\\n", "Holberton");
.br
prints "Hello Holberton" followed by a newline.

.B _printf("Number: %d\\n", -42);
.br
prints "Number: -42" followed by a newline.

.B _printf("Pi: %f\\n", 3.141592);
.br
prints "Pi: 3.141592" followed by a newline.

.B _printf("Rate: 100%%\\n");
.br
prints "Rate: 100%" followed by a newline.

.B _printf("[%q]\\n");
.br
prints "[%q]" followed by a newline in this implementation.

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3),
.BR write (2)
